The dreſs of the Tunguſe is much like that of the Jakutes, but very different from that of moſt other eaſtern nations, which, according to Mr. Fiſcher, Profeſſor of the Academy of Sciences at Peterſburg, who was among that people ſome time, conſiſts of a fur-habit, which they wear next the ſkin, ſhort trowſers, and long ſtockings, or boots, for they anſwer both purpoſes, drawn up tight and ſmooth to the leg, and faſtenened to the trowſers. Theſe ſtockings are ſoled and embroidered, ornamented with glaſs beads, and fringed. They faſten their breeches with a ſtring, which runs through the waiſtband, to which is tied, in part, a ſmall leather apron, cut into a great many ſlips, like fringe. The coat-ſleeves are cloſe, the ſkirts reach no lower than the knees, the borders are edged with fur, and the collars are embroidered, two inches broad, and fringed with a white hair, about four inches deep. Sometimes, the ſeams are covered with glaſs beads, ſtriped with


blue and white paint. They wear no girdle, but faſten their pipes and tobacco-pouch, flint, ſteel and knife, to the waiſtband of their trowſers. Under their coat they wear a waiſtcoat, that does not cloſe entirely on the breaſt, but faſtens with thongs: and, to defend their boſoms from the cold, they wear, in winter, a kind of breaſt-plate, neatly ornamented with glaſs beads, and covered with long dyed hair, or goat's ſkin, four inches broad, and ſeven or eight long. This hangs round the neck, and reaches to the ſtomach. Some wear, over this breaſt-plate, in hopes of good fortune, an iron idol, repreſenting a human figure, or that of a beaſt, or bird. In winter, they wear, over over theſe, ſtockings, or boots, buſkins that reach half way the leg, made of white rein-deer ſkin. To give them a ſavage appearance, they trim their cloaths with fur; and many fix large tufts of black, white, or red hair, 15 or 16 inches long, at their hips, and delight in ſeeing them float in the air. In ſummer, they go bare-headed; but, in winter, wear a cap made of the ſkin of the head of ſome horned animal, a rein-deer, goat, &c. and ſo contrive it, that the ears and horns of the animal being left on, are ſet erect on the head. They tie their hair cloſe behind, and let it hang down looſe on the back; and where they tie their hair, they have a bunch of beads (The women dreſs exactly like the men). Many of the men mark their faces with blue dots, in irregular figures; as do the Americans, and Greenlanders. This ornament is eſteemed a beauty;


and mothers imprint them on their children, by drawing a thread, blacked with ſoot and ſpittle, under the epidermis, which at firſt inflames the part, but leaves an indelible, blue mark. In ſummer, as a protection from the flies, they hang a bunch of horſe-hair over their ſhoulders; and every one carries the ſoft, ſhining ſkin, taken from a drake's head, with which they wipe the ſmall flies from their eyes. (See Pl. p. 125, Vol. 4.)

The Kuriles are better able to buy good cloaths than the Kamtſchadales; for the former can purchaſe, for one ſea-beaver, as much as the latter can for twenty foxes; and, one beaver, coſts a Kurilian no more trouble in catching him, than five foxes do a Kamtſchadale;




INSIDE OF A KAMTSCHADALE HOUSE



for the latter muſt be a good hunter, that catches more than 10 foxes in a winter; whereas, a Kurilian thinks himſelf unlucky, if he does not catch three beavers in the ſeaſon; beſides the numbers that are caſt on ſhore, by ſtorms.
